62
00:03:23,643 --> 00:03:26,444
It has some peculiar characteristics that other countries don't have.

63
00:03:27,145 --> 00:03:30,907
For one thing, your input to one of these stories is intermittent.

64
00:03:32,127 --> 00:03:34,268
The story is not listening to the player all the time.

65
00:03:34,877 --> 00:03:36,938
It can't, it's not allowed to for legal reasons,

66
00:03:37,058 --> 00:03:37,819
privacy reasons.

67
00:03:38,119 --> 00:03:39,939
You as the developer are not permitted

68
00:03:39,979 --> 00:03:41,940
to just open up the microphone and listen all the time.

69
00:03:42,000 --> 00:03:43,981
So turn-taking has to happen.

70
00:03:44,401 --> 00:03:45,742
And it's super important for the audience

71
00:03:45,782 --> 00:03:47,383
to know when it is their turn to talk.

72
00:03:48,243 --> 00:03:50,704
So for that, we use very explicit prompts.

73
00:03:51,144 --> 00:03:53,545
And you could use a sound effect or a bell

74
00:03:53,605 --> 00:03:54,265
or something like that,

75
00:03:54,305 --> 00:03:56,807
but we like to stay in fantasy with everything if we can.

76
00:03:57,467 --> 00:03:59,328
So the way we do it is we just have a character

77
00:03:59,488 --> 00:04:02,489
ask the player a direct question at some point in the story.

78
00:04:03,029 --> 00:04:05,490
And then you, the player, are expected to answer that question.

79
00:04:05,530 --> 00:04:07,651
That's how we let you know, okay, it's your turn.

80
00:04:08,731 --> 00:04:10,992
There's a writing corollary to that,

81
00:04:11,252 --> 00:04:14,813
which is that that is the only time that anybody asks anybody

82
00:04:14,853 --> 00:04:16,654
a direct question in one of our stories.

83
00:04:17,814 --> 00:04:21,496
And having to write a whole couple of hours worth of audio

84
00:04:21,996 --> 00:04:24,597
in which the characters do not ask each other direct questions

85
00:04:24,677 --> 00:04:26,818
and never speak in rhetorical questions

86
00:04:27,598 --> 00:04:30,519
strikes writers as strange and uncomfortable at first.

87
00:04:31,246 --> 00:04:33,007
It's not, though, as hard as it sounds.

88
00:04:33,027 --> 00:04:33,627
You get used to it.

89
00:04:35,547 --> 00:04:38,828
Second characteristic is you must make your decisions

90
00:04:38,868 --> 00:04:41,069
quickly in these stories.

91
00:04:41,109 --> 00:04:43,930
Alexa, for example, gives you 10 seconds to talk,

92
00:04:44,050 --> 00:04:45,610
and then it'll shut the microphone off

93
00:04:45,650 --> 00:04:47,071
if you haven't started saying something.

94
00:04:48,051 --> 00:04:49,631
It'll repeat the question one time,

95
00:04:49,651 --> 00:04:51,452
and then it'll shut the skill down entirely.

96
00:04:51,932 --> 00:04:54,233
So you have to be able to make that decision quickly.

97
00:04:54,493 --> 00:04:57,674
This is mostly also about not leaving the microphone

98
00:04:57,714 --> 00:04:59,234
open for privacy reasons.

99
00:05:00,548 --> 00:05:03,170
So for that, we just make sure that when it is your turn

100
00:05:03,210 --> 00:05:06,533
to make a decision, your options there are clear, simple,

101
00:05:07,054 --> 00:05:08,455
and they are few in number,

102
00:05:09,016 --> 00:05:11,898
and we enumerate them for you right then and there.

103
00:05:12,179 --> 00:05:13,660
And so that dictates the nature

104
00:05:13,680 --> 00:05:15,622
of how you would write that prompt.

105
00:05:15,682 --> 00:05:18,925
It's sort of a quick summation of your options

106
00:05:18,965 --> 00:05:19,966
at that point in the story.

107
00:05:22,212 --> 00:05:24,973
Thing three, voice recognition is really cool,

108
00:05:25,033 --> 00:05:27,973
