109
00:05:28,974 --> 00:05:31,954
So with someone who is mumbling,

110
00:05:32,314 --> 00:05:34,215
or turning away from the microphone,

111
00:05:34,395 --> 00:05:35,755
or maybe standing in a kitchen

112
00:05:35,795 --> 00:05:37,415
where dinner is actively being prepared,

113
00:05:37,435 --> 00:05:38,736
the sound can get kind of muddy.

114
00:05:39,396 --> 00:05:41,236
And if you give the voice recognition muddy sound,

115
00:05:41,256 --> 00:05:43,117
it has a much harder time doing its job.

116
00:05:43,137 --> 00:05:44,297
It's easy for it to get confused.

117
00:05:45,677 --> 00:05:47,277
So we try to make it easier

118
00:05:47,398 --> 00:05:48,738
on the voice recognition itself by.

119
00:05:49,574 --> 00:05:54,678
making its decisions easier, and we make the things that it is listening for also clearly

120
00:05:54,738 --> 00:05:56,400
distinct and few in number.

121
00:05:56,520 --> 00:06:01,544
So we offer the player clear options, but we also offer them specific ways to say what

122
00:06:01,564 --> 00:06:05,307
they want, and we carefully manage those phrases, again, part of the writing of these things,

123
00:06:05,988 --> 00:06:10,312
so that they do not sound similar to one another, and all of that makes it easier for the voice

124
00:06:10,332 --> 00:06:15,236
recognition to do its job under difficult circumstances, which difficult circumstances

125
00:06:15,296 --> 00:06:16,537
are more common than you might think.

126
00:06:18,554 --> 00:06:21,796
These prompts tend to get a little awkward,

127
00:06:21,836 --> 00:06:23,938
